DDL (Data Definition Language) refers to the SQL commands used to define, modify, and manage the structure of database objects such as tables, schemas, views, and indexes.

üëâ DDL commands affect the structure of the database, not the data itself.

üîπ Common DDL Commands

Command	Full Form	Purpose
CREATE- Create	Creates new database objects (e.g., tables, views)
ALTER -	Alter	Modifies an existing database object
DROP -	Drop	Deletes a database object permanently
TRUNCATE - Truncate	Removes all records from a table, but keeps its structure
RENAME- Rename	Renames a database object

üîπ 1. CREATE ‚Äì Create Database Objects
‚û§ Purpose:

Used to create new tables, databases, views, or other objects.

‚û§ Syntax:
CREATE TABLE table_name (
    column1 datatype constraint,
    column2 datatype constraint,
    ...
);

‚û§ Example:
CREATE TABLE Employees (
    EmpID INT PRIMARY KEY,
    EmpName VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,
    Department VARCHAR(30),
    Salary DECIMAL(10, 2),
    HireDate DATE
);


‚úÖ Explanation:

EmpID ‚Äì integer, unique identifier (Primary Key)

EmpName ‚Äì variable-length string, cannot be null

Department ‚Äì string up to 30 chars

Salary ‚Äì numeric with 2 decimal places

HireDate ‚Äì date of joining

üîπ 2. ALTER ‚Äì Modify Existing Objects
‚û§ Purpose:

Used to add, modify, or delete columns or constraints in an existing table.

‚û§ Syntax:
ALTER TABLE table_name
ADD column_name datatype;

ALTER TABLE table_name
MODIFY column_name datatype;

ALTER TABLE table_name
DROP COLUMN column_name;

‚û§ Examples:
‚û§ Add a new column:
ALTER TABLE Employees
ADD Email VARCHAR(100);

‚û§ Modify data type of a column:
ALTER TABLE Employees
MODIFY Salary DECIMAL(12, 2);

‚û§ Drop a column:
ALTER TABLE Employees
DROP COLUMN HireDate;

üîπ 3. DROP ‚Äì Delete Database Objects
‚û§ Purpose:

Used to remove an entire database object (like a table, view, or database).

‚û§ Syntax:
DROP TABLE table_name;

‚û§ Example:
DROP TABLE Employees;


‚ö†Ô∏è Note: Once dropped, the table and all its data are permanently deleted.

üîπ 4. TRUNCATE ‚Äì Remove All Data (Keep Structure)
‚û§ Purpose:

Used to remove all rows from a table, but keep the table structure for future use.

‚û§ Syntax:
TRUNCATE TABLE table_name;

‚û§ Example:
TRUNCATE TABLE Employees;


‚úÖ Difference between TRUNCATE and DELETE:

Feature	                        TRUNCATE	                                    DELETE
Removes rows                  	All rows	                                Specific rows (with WHERE)
Rollback (Undo)                	Not always possible	                      Possible
Resets Identity (Auto Increment)	Yes	                                     No
Speed	                           Faster                                 	Slower

üîπ 5. RENAME ‚Äì Change the Name of an Object
‚û§ Purpose:

Used to rename a database object (like a table).

‚û§ Syntax (varies by SQL dialect):
In Oracle SQL:
RENAME old_table_name TO new_table_name;

In MySQL / SQL Server:
ALTER TABLE old_table_name RENAME TO new_table_name;

‚û§ Example:
ALTER TABLE Employees RENAME TO Staff;

üîπ Summary Table
Command	                                                           Purpose	                                                             Example
CREATE	                                                Creates new table or object	                                               CREATE TABLE Employees (...);
ALTER	                                                  Modifies table structure	                                                 ALTER TABLE Employees ADD Email VARCHAR(100);
DROP	                                                     Deletes table permanently	                                             DROP TABLE Employees;
TRUNCATE                                              	Removes all data, keeps structure	                                         TRUNCATE TABLE Employees;
RENAME	                                                Renames an object	                                                         ALTER TABLE Employees RENAME TO Staff;

